I have written some highly unoptimized code for factoring integers using
Lenstra's elliptic curve method, with the "birthday paradox" phase two
developed by Richard Brent.  Even at this stage, it can factor the seventh
Fermat number 2^2^7+1 in 352 seconds, as opposed to 1877 seconds by the
in-built factoring method.  If anybody is interesting in developing this
code further, do let me know.

-Alasdair

------=_Part_27980_22398390.1184072916921
Content-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

I have written some highly unoptimized code for factoring integers using Lenstra&#39;s elliptic curve method, with the &quot;birthday paradox&quot; phase two developed by Richard Brent.&nbsp; Even at this stage, it can factor the seventh Fermat number 2^2^7+1 in 352 seconds, as opposed to 1877 seconds by the in-built factoring method.&nbsp; If anybody is interesting in developing this code further, do let me know.
<br><br>-Alasdair<br>

